HEADWORD: euphrasy
<hw>eu"phra*sy</hw> <pr>(⟦umac⟧"fr⟦adot⟧*s⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[NL. <ets>euphrasia</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>e'yfrasi`a</grk> delight,
fr. <grk>e'yfrai`nein</grk> to delight; <grk>e'y^</grk> well +
<grk>frh`n</grk> heart, mind: cf. LL. <ets>eufrasia</ets>, F.
<ets>eufraise</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The plant
<altname>eyebright</altname> (<spn>Euphrasia officionalis</spn>),
formerly regarded as beneficial in disorders of the eyes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then purged with <qex>euphrasy</qex> and rue⟦br⟧
